[normal]Written evidence submitted by The Crown Estate (CCS19)[bold]Summary:[bold]The key messages articulated below can be summarised as the following:-[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]The Crown Estate welcomes the opportunity to submit evidence to
[normal] the
[normal] Commons Select Committee inquiry into carbon capture and storage (CCS)
[normal].
[normal]  
[normal]T
[normal]he focus of our
[normal] response 
[normal]is 
[normal]on the offshore transport and storage components
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]as this is where we are able to bring to bear an in
[normal]-
[normal]depth understanding of the potential benefits that 
[normal]CCS could have
[normal],
[normal] as well as the barriers to development and ways to overcome them
[normal]. 
[normal] The statements contained are in the context of The Crown Estate’s role and 
[normal]responsibilities with 
[normal]regards to 
[normal]rights to leasing of carbon dioxide transportation and storage in
[normal]frastructure 
[normal]within areas 
[normal]on 
[normal]and beneath 
[normal]the 
[normal]UK 
[normal]seabed
[normal] that we manage
[normal]. 
[normal] 
[normal]The Crown Estate has been working with
[normal] the CCS
[normal] industry
[normal] on project specific cases, (including power station developers, potential industrial users and potential storage providers)
[normal] 
[normal]as
[normal] well as 
[normal]through the CCS Cost Reduction Task Force
[normal] in 2012/13, which was chaired by the CCSA, 
[normal]to identify ways of 
[normal]helping to 
[normal]reduc
[normal]e
[normal] the cost of 
[normal]deploying 
[normal]CCS infrastructure
[normal] and promoting an intelligent systems design in the 2020s. 
[normal]The Task Force signalled 
[normal]the importance of storage to the cost and deployment of this technology and highlighted 
[normal]aspects
[normal] such as 
[normal]storage 
[normal]site availability and 
[normal]store 
[normal]viability as being critical to its delivery. 
[normal] We are now leading an industry Transport and Storage Development Group
[normal] to take forward recommendations of the Task Force and assist delivery of proven storage sites and transport infrastructure.
[normal]During the past year, we signed the UK’s first two Agreements for Lease for the permanent geological storage of CO2, representing a
[normal] positive milestone in the plan to build a demonstration project in the UK. These agreements provide exclusive time-limited options with pre-agreed terms for leases, allowing developers to progress their projects through to a Final Investment Decision (FID
[normal]).
[normal]We suggest that any policy developed for CCS needs to enable opportunistic deployment for all sectors that can make use of the infrastructure, e.g. the offshore oil and gas sector (enhanced oil recovery (EOR) &amp; enhanced gas recovery (EGR)), 
[normal]natural gas 
[normal]processing, coal and gas fired power generation, and 
[normal]industrial 
[normal]processes such as iron and steel
[normal].  
[normal]In order to de-risk the delivery of the UK’s aspirations for energy security, decarbonisation and retention of its industries in a low carbon world, w
[normal]e belie
[normal]ve that domestic policy should support a clear route to market across 
[normal]all 
[normal]these
[normal] sectors
[normal] 
[normal]that can leverage an early clear
[normal] route to market for the power sector.
[normal]In
[normal] our view policy should help drive both ends of the 
[normal]CCS 
[normal]chain (capture, along with transport and storage) towards 
[normal]deployment of 
[normal]full chain 
[normal]infrastructure
[normal] (through incentives and obligations)
[normal],
[normal] as well as clearly setting out how this sits alongside the wider discussion on energy security.  This should include pro
[normal]viding incentives for bringing storage forward at a pace that delivers de-risked stores, in parallel with designing and developing new low carbon fossil fuel power stations.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Questions posed in call for evidence:[bold]Each of the questions asked by the Committee has been considered in turn. 
[normal] 
[normal]We have focused the submission of evidence primarily on those 
[normal]in which we can add most value 
[normal]from the experience we have gained 
[normal]in our role 
[normal]at
[normal] The Crown Estate
[normal].
[normal]It was clear from our work on the cost reduction taskforce that 
[normal]capture 
[normal]technology providers will be able to answer this in far more precise detail 
[normal]than 
[normal]we could offer on post
[normal]-combustion, pre-combustion or oxyfuel techniques and product delivery.
[normal]  The capabilities of CO
[normal]2
[normal] transport and storage technologies have been demonstrated elsewhere, for example in North America and Norway, over many years and experience in these operation
[normal]s is best provided by the oil and gas industry.
[normal]It is widely acknowledged
[normal] that tackling climate change requires 
[normal]a 
[normal]glo
[normal]bal 
[normal]response
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal] 
[normal]The International Energy Agency
[normal] (IEA)
[normal] considers successful deployment of CCS as critical to global efforts 
[normal]in
[normal] mitigat
[normal]ing
[normal] climate change and to keep
[normal]ing
[normal] global warming 
[normal]temperature rises 
[normal]below 2°C.
[normal] 
[normal]For the UK
[normal], the 80% reduction in greenhouse ga
[normal]ses by 2050 (as defined by the Climate Change Act 2008) requires a significant 
[normal]change in the way we generate and use energy
[normal]. Projections from the Committee on Climate Change show that the power sector will need to be largely decarbonised by around 2030 in 
[normal]order to be on track to hit the 2050 targets (given the difficulties in achieving emissions reductions elsewhere in the economy
[normal])
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]Many alternate scenarios can be created as to what the energy mix could or should 
[normal]look like 
[normal]in the future
[normal]; but one thing which seems clear is that by just shifting the fossil fuel use from coal to gas will not in itself deliver the targets that are required in the Climate Change Act
[normal] (2008)
[normal] – particularly given the 
[normal]extent of 
[normal]“locked-in” fossil fuel plant, whic
[normal]h has been made 
[normal]more certain
[normal] by the gas generation strategy and the grandfathering of gas plants
[normal] under the Emissions Performance Standard
[normal].  
[normal]CCS can be used with both coal or gas power stations and therefore early deployment of transport and storage infrast
[normal]ructure can provide an effective hedge, keeping options open for 
[normal]either fuel within the nation’s 
[normal]low carbon 
[normal]portfolio.
[normal]Both DECC and the Committee on Climate Change identify the primary options for power sector decarbonisation to 2030 as (in no particular 
[normal]order): large scale renewables, nuclear, CCS, and energy efficiency. DECC’s CCS Roadmap identifies that CCS has the potential to be one of the most cost effective technologies for decarbonisation of the UK’s power and industrial sectors. In the power secto
[normal]r, CCS has a unique 
[normal]place 
[normal]in providing a continuing role for flexible fossil fuel capacity that is able to respond to demand in the way that other low carbon technologies 
[normal]can
[normal]not. 
[normal]Of course it is understood that the three-stage process of CCS, including tra
[normal]nsportation and storage, has yet to be demonstrated on large scale power stations, which is why the successful deployment of projects in the DECC commercialisation programme is critical.
[normal]Beyond the power sector, 
[normal]CCS is almost unique in its 
[normal]potential 
[normal]to hel
[normal]p reduce emissions from industries where there are no alternative abatement technologies e.g. cement
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]fertiliser 
[normal]and 
[normal]steel 
[normal]production processes
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal] 
[normal]Whilst we feel that CCS power projects are likely to come before industrial CCS; smaller scale industrial proj
[normal]ects do need to start sooner rather than later in order to leverage synergies wherever possible to ensure that learning occurs in sufficient time to hit decarbonisation targets beyond 2030.
[normal] 
[normal] 
[normal]DECC and the Committee on Climate Change have outlined 
[normal]a wide ran
[normal]ge of scenarios for the relative contribution 
[normal]of low carbon technologies 
[normal]in recent publications
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]Figure 1: DECC Scenarios [bold]for installed capacity in [bold]2030[bold] (GW)[bold]Figure 2: CCC Scenarios [bold]for installed capacity in [bold]2030[bold] (GW) – note that all the scenarios presented reach a power sector emissions intensity of 50g/KWh[bold]Our observations on these scenarios are as follows:
[normal]-
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The scenarios 
[normal]demonstrate that CCS could potentially make a very significant contribution to decarbonisa
[normal]tion by 2030 – with up to 15GW of capacity envisaged.
[normal]-
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]As the level of ambition for 2030 power sector decarbonisation increases, the need for CCS to make a contribution also increases. CCS makes a very significant contribution to all of the scenarios which 
[normal]hit 50g/KWh by 2030 (for example 9GW in DECC’s scenarios; 10-15GW in CCC’s scenarios).
[normal]-
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]CCS could play an important balancing role alongside other low carbon technologies such as nuclear and renewables.
[normal]-
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The risk of not developing CCS is that decarbonisation
[normal] options become more limited, and power sector decarbonisation becomes much harder to achieve.
[normal]-
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Whilst
[normal] the scenarios show potential for CCS, they also highlight the uncertainty 
[normal]power generators face in making investment decisions without targeted policies t
[normal]hat go beyond the renewables focus of t
[normal]he EMR Delivery Plan
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]In order to give greater confidence to the CCS industry, it will be important for the government to provide
[normal] early and 
[normal]consistent signals over the level of ambition for decarbonisation
[normal]; and f
[normal]urth
[normal]er 
[normal]details on 
[normal]to how CCS 
[normal]will be supported 
[normal]beyond the current commercialisation programme
[normal]. It will be important to consider the contribution CCS can make in reducing industrial emissions as well as power sector emissions. 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]T
[normal]he storage space (and use of) in the North Sea 
[normal]creates an
[normal] export opportunit
[normal]y
[normal] 
[normal]for sell
[normal]ing
[normal] the service of permanently dispos
[normal]ed
[normal] 
[normal]CO
[normal]2
[normal] 
[normal]that 
[normal]originat
[normal]ed
[normal] from
[normal] European countries need
[normal]ing
[normal] 
[normal]storage
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal] Many countries will be looking to the North Sea rather than using dry land storage potential.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]In relation to 
[normal]a
[normal] 
[normal]North Sea 
[normal]“storage market”
[normal], there is an opportunity for large scale deployment through the development of infrastructure (pipelines to storage) in a coordinated manner. 
[normal]I
[normal]t would seem prudent for the UK, Norway, the Netherlands and other North 
[normal]Sea
[normal] basin countries to collaborate in o
[normal]rder to drive forward early projects.
[normal] 
[normal] 
[normal]This would help to increase trade and supply chain opportunities
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Potential 
[normal]economic opportunities 
[normal]will exist 
[normal]for UK supply chains that currently support the North Sea oil and gas industry
[normal].  If a CO
[normal]2
[normal] transport and st
[normal]orage sector is encouraged to develop it will be possible to transfer skills, services and supply chains from oil and gas construction and operations.  Any decline in North Sea activity could be compensated for in CTS activity.  Growth could also be possib
[normal]le if CTS 
[normal]deployment
[normal] was to leverage oil and gas activity in both conventional storage and CO
[normal]2
[normal] enhanced hydrocarbon recovery.  
[normal]Any roll-out of CCS power and industrial plant will increase the need for supply chains providing capture technologies and associ
[normal]ated services. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The Crown Estate is very supportive of the
[normal] £1bn commercialisation programme capital grant and 
[normal]contract for difference
[normal] support 
[normal]being provided by the Government 
[normal]for the two early projects
[normal] – these projects will help understand deployment 
[normal]and operational barriers along with the viability
[normal] 
[normal]of full scale
[normal] CCS power generation. 
[normal]In a European context this is very progressive and 
[normal]an excellent kick-start for
[normal] the sector.  
[normal]This section will focus on 
[normal]where we see the barriers that can potentially prevent CCS being a viable option for energy decarbonisation and 
[normal]which can create a gap between aspiration and delivery in the UK.
[normal] 
[normal] 
[normal]These 
[normal]barriers 
[normal]can be seen as risks that need to be managed and mitigated.  W
[normal]e have provided some suggestions for 
[normal]mitigating these risks
[normal].
[normal]Contract[bold]s[bold] for Difference[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]The EMR framework 
[normal]offers 
[normal]a
[normal] suite of measures to support and encourage the deployment of non-commercial technologies for energy system decarbonisation. In respect of CCS, it is
[normal] 
[normal]the 
[normal]Contract for Difference Feed in Tariff 
[normal](
[normal]CfD FiT
[normal])
[normal] that will be used initially to remunerate b
[normal]oth of th
[normal]e projects 
[normal]that are currently preferred bidders in the DECC 
[normal]commercialisation 
[normal]competition
[normal]. This FiT is suitable for the first demonstration projects alongside capital grants because they are full chain and have an integrated transport and storage solution 
[normal]allowing for risk and liability sharing to be established ahead of final investment decision (FID).
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]CfD FiT focuses on
[normal], and is designed for, 
[normal]the investment risks involved in power generation projects.  
[normal]As with the first commercialisation project
[normal]s
[normal], this ap
[normal]proach only 
[normal]addresses 
[normal]the risk and risk sharing for full chain CCS projects.  
[normal]However t
[normal]ransport and permanent storage of CO
[normal]2
[normal] as a disposal service face
[normal]s
[normal] a number of complex investment and deployment issues with risks that are quite different from those in 
[normal]power generation.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]In order for 
[normal]future CCS 
[normal]projects to benefit from CfD FiTs, they will 
[normal]therefor 
[normal]need to have reached agreement across the full CCS chain.  Power generators generally do not have the expertise to develop CO
[normal]2
[normal] transport and storage solutions,
[normal] and are dependent on third parties to agree novel business structures and counterparty arrangements to deal with the complex new value chain.  
[normal]Under the EMR framework there is therefor
[normal]e
[normal] a significant drag on 
[normal]power generators even being able to negotiate a
[normal] CfD.  Furthermore, 
[normal]who, without an incentive, could deliver transport and storage infrastructure ahead of a guaranteed income?
[normal] 
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Another barrier to the development of efficiently sized CTS infrastructure under EMR arises because 
[normal]CfD FiT 
[normal] funding 
[normal]is directed 
[normal]to the power 
[normal]generator 
[normal]only
[normal].  A
[normal]s power plant developers will not build capture plant without guaranteed assurances of access to a transport and storage
[normal] solution
[normal] 
[normal]project development will
[normal] likely 
[normal]be 
[normal]limit
[normal]ed
[normal] to point to point projects rather than e
[normal]ncourage over sizing and sharing of infrastructure.
[normal] 
[normal] 
[normal]K
[normal]ey to the success of CCS 
[normal]delivery 
[normal]will be avoid
[normal]ing the
[normal] uncoordinated deployment of full chain integrated projects over the next decade
[normal], as this would
[normal] do little to promote a
[normal]n integrated
[normal] transport infrast
[normal]ructure 
[normal]approach 
[normal]or the development of storage hubs
[normal] – both of which will lead to substantial cost reductions
[normal]. 
[normal] 
[normal]Such ‘point to point’ CCS projects will suffer economically from having 
[normal]unnecessarily 
[normal]expensive transport and storage systems.
[normal] 
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Because of thes
[normal]e timing, business model and coordination barriers, a significant risk therefor
[normal]e
[normal] exists that CCS will not become a viable option for power generators because the necessary disposal infrastructure will not be independently built.
[normal]  
[normal]The Crown Estate is develo
[normal]ping an understanding of the market failures that we believe will stand in the way of the development of a mature CTS infrastructure and therefor
[normal]e
[normal] CCS as a viable power generation option.  Workshops with industry representatives have provided a comprehensi
[normal]ve background to various sources of market failures impeding the development of CTS infrastructure. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The activities of Capture, Transport and Storage of CO
[normal]2
[normal] differ by industry type, risk/return profile and their development stage and must therefore be tac
[normal]kled appropriately. 
[normal]Storage development lead times can 
[normal]be 
[normal]around 10
[normal] years 
[normal]for a new unexplored site 
[normal]compared to an average of 5 years for power generation projects.
[normal] 
[normal] 
[normal]Encouraging up-front investment in de-risking storage and providing ’proven and bankable’ 
[normal]stores will need to be a key policy focus.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]In light of the above, 
[normal]The Crown Estate believes there are risks 
[normal]in the current approach to
[normal] 
[normal]‘
[normal]rolling out
[normal]’
[normal] CCS on power generation beyond the demonstration phase 
[normal]and we see that this could be addressed through 
[normal]enhancing EMR with additional interventions that recognise the particular complexities of the CCS value chain
[normal]. 
[normal] 
[normal]The power sector needs to see the 
[normal]requirement and purpose
[normal] 
[normal]of 
[normal]CCS and needs to have the storage solutions delivered to them.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Capacity Market[bold]We suggest that existing government policy for CCS and 
[normal]the 
[normal]EMR 
[normal]capacity mechanism 
[normal]in combination with the gas generation strategy and 
[normal]Carbon Capture Readiness (
[normal]CCR
[normal])
[normal] creates
[normal] 
[normal]a further barrier to the development transport and storage infrastructure due to no
[normal] clear imperative for developers to invest in CO
[normal]2
[normal] disposal.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The Capacity Market
[normal] 
[normal]is 
[normal]designed 
[normal]to ensure there is sufficient capacity in place to cope with peaks and troughs in demand.  This can, however, lead to a large amount of money 
[normal]being spent on
[normal] plan
[normal]t
[normal]s
[normal] with ever-decreasing load factors over the next 15-20 years.  The alternative is that this plant is fitted with CCS and efficiently utili
[normal]s
[normal]es a transport and storage infrastructure 
[normal]solution 
[normal]that has been facilitated through smart policies in addition to 
[normal]EMR.
[normal]  
[normal]ETI energy system modelling has indicated that deployment of CCS-equipped power generation will lead to a lower overall cost of decarbonisation for the UK economy. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Carbon Price[bold]Carbon pricing can only influence power generator behaviour not
[normal] that of
[normal] the companies who are potential
[normal] CTS 
[normal]infrastructure 
[normal]developers.  Whilst the carbon price floor can be a market mechanism to drive investment 
[normal]by producers of carbon emissions 
[normal]it does 
[normal]exacerbate the timing, coordination and 
[normal]phasing problem 
[normal]highlighted above.
[normal]  Without a penalty on emissions commensurate with the cost of building the full CCS chain there are not likely to be investment
[normal]s
[normal] 
[normal]in CTS infrastructure.  With the current carbon price floor trajectory
[normal] 
[normal]there is a high risk that 
[normal]investment decisions 
[normal]on CCS-e
[normal]quipped gas power plants would not be influenced
[normal] 
[normal]until 
[normal]the mid-late 2020s.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Industrial CCS[bold]Industrial decarbonisation is likely to require its own bespoke set of policies and support interventions.  However, it will require CTS infrastructure to be in 
[normal]place in advance if the least cost pathway is to be achieved and to ensure that industry is not adversely affected.  Logically this means that the use of CTS in power should be planned and designed with the whole system in mind.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]O[bold]vercom[bold]ing[bold] the barriers[bold]To
[normal] 
[normal]de-risk the viability of CCS as cost effective decarbonisation option 
[normal]policy interventions 
[normal]are required to address 
[normal]the structural problem 
[normal]that
[normal] C
[normal]O2 transport and storage needs 
[normal]a development pathway in parallel to EMR
[normal]. 
[normal] 
[normal]As it stands, EMR requires all CTS i
[normal]nfrastructure to be funded from payments made to the power station (a trickle-down funding approach).  
[normal]An alternative would be a direct revenue stream for transporting and storing CO
[normal]2
[normal], which results in removing (or lowering) one element of contractual risk
[normal] for both the power station and the transport/store operator.
[normal] 
[normal] As all of the initial projects would by definition, need to be full chain, direct funding for the CTS infrastructure would not significantly impact the risk for early projects.  Any payment to 
[normal]the Transport and Store would net directly off payments that would have been made to the power station under EMR.  Once multiple CCS projects are operating in the UK
[normal],
[normal] direct funding can reduce risk for all parties by providing greater price certainty and l
[normal]ower contract
[normal]ual
[normal] risk.  The eventual contracting structure that arises in the industry will partially dictate the impact of this intervention.
[normal] 
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Revenue 
[normal]c
[normal]ould most likely come from the CfD FiT
[normal] funding body that is paid via a levy on suppliers and be delivered in the form of a fee per tonne of CO
[normal]2
[normal].  If the revenue would otherwise have been supplied by a CfD FiT such a scheme could be reasonably cost-neutral.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Information on most of the potential storage sites in the UKCS is still sparse. 
[normal] 
[normal]Collection of the necessary data is time-consuming and at the later stages of site characterisation costly. The gap between initial site screening and operation therefore puts
[normal] significant capital at risk. 
[normal] 
[normal]This will be most noticeable when developing new geological formations.  Not surprisingly, storage is therefore currently regarded as the most risky part of the CCS chain for project developers.
[normal] 
[normal]Specifically targeted storage 
[normal]exploration subsidies focused on early-stage development of the industry, could be used to target ‘new’ areas of storage or incremental work at existing storage sites (which would bring wider benefits).  
[normal]A lower limit on
[normal] 
[normal]pre-FID exploration and appraisal
[normal] c
[normal]ost 
[normal]is likely to be 
[normal]in the region of 
[normal]+
[normal]£
[normal]50
[normal]m per storage site
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal] The incentive could be relatively revenue neutral for Government if it was associated with a project which would otherwise have required a higher CfD FiT. 
[normal] 
[normal]Any
[normal] exploration subsidies could encou
[normal]rage early appraisal of storage and provide benefits through the de-risking of the wider storage area and gains from knowledge sharing to the CTS industry.
[normal]Investment in storage site appraisal could 
[normal]also 
[normal]be encouraged through different tax break options. O
[normal]ne option is 
[normal]a c
[normal]ross-sector tax break which would allow losses or some form of ‘allowances for investment’ to be transferred from the CCS industry to other activities undertaken by the same company even if it is completely outside the CCS sphere. 
[normal] 
[normal]For exam
[normal]ple if a potential s
[normal]torage developer
[normal] was able to expense &gt;100% of their exploration cost against oil/gas income this could act as a sufficient primer
[normal].  
[normal]This can change the perspective of oil and gas operators late in a field life if they could appraise fro
[normal]m their platform and potentially convert the facility. 
[normal] 
[normal]Its key benefit would be to encourage companies who would otherwise not be involved in CCS to get involved and provide equity at the early stage of the industry roll-out.  It could help
[normal] to
[normal] incentivise
[normal] oil companies who due to their skills and expertise are seen as key stakeholders but have no incentive to get involved at present into the sector.
[normal] 
[normal]Tax breaks could be relatively revenue neutral for Government as an improvement in project economics through a tax break should enable a lower CfD FiT price to be paid to power stations offsetting the loss in tax revenue.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The
[normal] setting 
[normal]of 
[normal]targets / emissi
[normal]on 
[normal]drivers offer
[normal] an understandable and robust commitment that would offer the power and storage industry the level of security it needs to invest in CCS. 
[normal] 
[normal]The lack of targets / emissions drivers for CO
[normal]2
[normal] emissions 
[normal]inevitably 
[normal]creates uncertainty for investor
[normal]s. 
[normal] A target 
[normal]c
[normal]ould be seen as a positive rather than a negative thing to
[normal] pursue
[normal].  
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Taking CCS from an early stage technology to a commercially viable one 
[normal]which is 
[normal]suitable for private sector development and widely adopted
[normal],
[normal] will require reducing the overal
[normal]l costs
[normal], 
[normal] includ
[normal]ing
[normal] the cost of capital sufficiently enough to make CCS commercially competitive with traditional generating technologies.
[normal] 
[normal] While the outcome from DECC’s commercialisation programme may result in one or two projects
[normal] being successfully devel
[normal]oped
[normal], the challenge will be how to maintain momentum among other projects 
[normal]which have been 
[normal]unsuccessful in obtaining DECC funding and 
[normal]to 
[normal]scale up the industry beyond that.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Support beyond EMR for follow-on projects needs to be progressed if the sector is to
[normal] be capable of ramping up, lowering costs and making a large scale contribution 
[normal]to the energy mix 
[normal]through
[normal]out
[normal] the 2020s. 
[normal] 
[normal]The first follow
[normal]-
[normal]on CCS projects will need to progress
[normal] (
[normal]potentially to 
[normal]FID),
[normal] before many learnings
[normal] have emerged from the projects supported by DECC’s commercialisation programme. 
[normal] 
[normal]Given the challenges identified for the sector
[normal],
[normal] there is a real risk that without targeted intervention
[normal],
[normal] follow-on projects will not emerge
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal] 
[normal]In the long
[normal] 
[normal]run
[normal],
[normal] projects need t
[normal]o be investable without the benefit of public funding
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal] 
[normal]T
[normal]his will require significant progress on a range of issues and 
[normal]is 
[normal]not 
[normal]able to 
[normal]be delivered by the market on its own.  Further targeted intervention is required to facilitate these developments and de
[normal]liver these opportunities.
[normal] 
[normal] This is not about capital grants as they do not resolve structural failings; instead smart design of policy drivers is required to bring forward the sector to invest in the technology on a realistic scale.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]We would propose that the two best starting places to cover these issues are the 
[normal]EU CCS Directive, which places 
[normal]very stringent requirements related to storage site selection, characterisation and monitoring
[normal], along with the FAQ’s that can be found at
