[normal]Norway 
[normal]incentivised the use 
[normal]of CCS 
[normal]in offshore 
[normal]gas pr
[normal]oduction 
[normal]through
[normal] a carbon tax, however similarly to the countries above there is an associated conventional business model in the production and sale of natural gas.  Norway has plans to 
[normal]deploy CCS on the combined heat and power plant 
[normal]at Mongstaad 
[normal](
[normal]with go
[normal]vernment support
[normal])
[normal], where there is an industrial scale test facility currently using waste gas from the refinery
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]In contrast to these countries, the UK’s approach for encouraging
[normal] CCS beyond the commercialisation programme relies on a mixture of policies using “carrots” and “sticks”, including CfD FiTs, Carbon price floor and the emissions performance standard.  
[normal]It is our view that carbon floor prices are not a driving force in th
[normal]e short to medium term unless they go immediately to £50 /tonne (or thereabouts).  This also means that the ETS is unlikely to drive European projects. By way of contrast, the Norwegian carbon tax was set at a level that meant avoiding emissions was
[normal] 
[normal]the pr
[normal]eferred outcome.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]In relation to the 
[normal]pricing of CO
[normal]2
[normal] emissions as a penalty 
[normal]and
[normal] its role in the delivery of CCS, we note that 
[normal]under the current UK carbon floor price trajectory of £30/tonne in 2020 rising to £70/tonne in 2030
[normal] 
[normal]the level at which 
[normal]power gene
[normal]rators 
[normal]would be incentivised to build CCS 
[normal]CCGTs
[normal] 
[normal]rather than pay the penalty 
[normal]would unlikely 
[normal]occur until the mid-late 2020’s at the earliest
[normal]. 
[normal] 
[normal]Therefor
[normal] unabated gas will remain 
[normal]a 
[normal]preference and transport and storage infrastructure will not be built until 
[normal]beyond the mid 2020’s
[normal]. 
[normal] 
[normal]This delay in deployment will mean costs will not be reduced ahead of essential use of the 
[normal]technology 
[normal]in 
[normal]the 2030’s
[normal] 
[normal]for achieving emissions targets 
[normal]in both power and 
[normal]industry
[normal]. 
